	<h3>echo::system </h3>
	<p>
		echo::system is a live performance and installation work, a response to our current global environmental crisis caused by contemporary humans' inability to reflect on our own impact to the natural world. The project uses live art and installation to illuminate the complex dynamic phenomena in our environment. Constructed environments, which we call ActionStations, parallel our “natural” environments. The second piece in a 5-part series, ActionStation #2 – The Desert looks at the geographic, historical and cultural conditions of the U.S. southwestern desert through simulating walks; pathways through the landscape on “smart” treadmills. Technology is employed both functionally and metaphorically in this work. The installation is a re-engineering of a conventional treadmill to evoke an embodied interaction, developing active and engaging mediated spaces to explore socio-cultural and ecological aspects of the desert Southwest that are not immediately apparent through contemporary means of travel.<br/><br/>
		Referencing the Walkabout, an indigenous practice of Aboriginal Australia, our treadmill walk extends the metaphor of an interface with the land to activate memory and integrate different levels of information. The performance juxtaposes the common treadmill of mechanically assisted walking with an actual walk and by “going nowhere” the performance affords the user opportunities to reflect in the best tradition of speculative fiction: creating an alternate reality, with re-mixed histories, timescales, and ecologies, promoting contemplation of our own past, present and future.<br/><br/>
		This project was generously supported by the Institute for Humanities Research at Arizona State University.
	</p>
